t to surprisingly hard if we\nallow � to be strange, e.g. a Koch snowflake.)\nDefinition: A region � in the plane is called simply connected if, for every simple closed curve\nthat lies entirely in � the interior of � also lies entirely in �.\nExamples:\nD1\nD2\nD3\nx\ny\nD4\nx\ny\nD5 = whole plane\nD1-D5 are simply connected, since for any simple closed curve inside them its interior is entirely\ninside the region. This is sometimes phrased as each region has \"no holes\".\nNote. An alternative definition, which works in higher dimensions is that the region is simply con\nnected if any curve in the region can be continuously shrunk to a point without leaving the region.\nThe regions at below are not simply connected. That is, the interior of the curve � is not entirely in\nthe region.\nC\nAnnulus\nx\ny\nC\nPuntured plane\n13 Potential theorem and conservative fields\nAs an application of Green's theorem we can now give a more complete answer to our question of\nhow to tell if a field is conservative. The theorem does not have a standard name, so we choose to\ncall it the Potential theorem. You should check that it is largely a restatement for simply connected\nregions of Theorem GT.17 above.\nTheorem GT.27. (Potential theorem) Take � = (�, �) defined and differentiable on a region �.\n(a) If � = �� then curl� = �� - �� = 0.\n(b) If � is simply connected and curl� = 0 on �, then � = �� for some � .\nNotes.\n1. We know that on a connected region, being a gradient field is equivalent to being conservative. So\nwe can restate the Potential theorem as: On a simply connected region, � is conservative is equivalent\nto curl� = 0.\n\n13 POTENTIAL THEOREM AND CONSERVATIVE FIELDS\n2. Recall that once we know work integral is path independent, we can compute the potential function\n� by picking a base point �0 in � and letting\n� (�) = ∫�\n� ⋅ ��,\nwhere � is any path in � from �0 to �.\nProof of (a): This was proved in Theorem GT.17.\nProof of (b): Suppose � is a simple clos