      "content": "18.04 Problem Set 3, Spring 2018\nCalendar\nT Feb. 20: Finish topic 2 notes\nW Feb. 21: Reading: Review of 18.02\nR Feb. 22: Recitation\nF Feb. 23: Reading: Topic 3 notes\nComing next\nFeb. 26-Mar. 2: Cauchy's theorem, Cauchy's integral formula\nProblem 1. (30: 10,10,10 points)\n(a) Compute ∫ z\n1 dz, where C is the unit circle around the point z = 2 traversed in the\nC\ncounterclockwise direction.\n(b) Show that ∫C z2 dz = 0 for any simple closed curve C in 2 ways.\n(i) Apply the fundamental theorem of complex line integrals\n(ii) Write out both the real and imaginary parts of the integral as 18.02 integrals of the\nform ∫C M dx + N dy and apply Green's theorem to each part.\n(c) Consider the integral ∫ z\n1 dz, where C is the unit circle. Write out both the real and\nC\nimaginary parts as 18.02 integrals, i.e. of the form ∫C M(x, y) dx+ N(x, y) dy.\nProblem 2. (20: 10,10 points)\n(a)\nLet C be the unit circle traversed counterclockwise. Directly from the definition of\ncomplex line integrals compute ∫ zdz.\nC\nIs this the same as ∫ z dz?\nC\n(b) Compute ∫ z2 dz for each of the following paths from 0 to 1 + i.\nC\n(i) The straight line connecting the two points.\n(ii) The path consisting of the line from 0 to 1 followed by the line from 1 to 1 + i.\nProblem 3. (20: 10,10 points)\nLet C be the circle of radius 1 centered at z = -4. Let f(z) = 1/(z + 4). and consider the\nline integral\nI = ∫f(z) dz.\nC\n(a) Does Cauchy's Theorem imply that I = 0? Why or why not?\n(b) Parametrize the curve C and carry out the calculation to find the value of I. Check\nthat the answer confirms your excellent reasoning in part (a).\n\n18.04 Problem Set 3, Spring 2018\nProblem 4. (10 points)\nLet C be a path from the point z1 = 0 to the point z2 = 1 + i. Find\nI = ∫z9 + cos(z) - ez dz\nC\nin the form I = a+ ib. Justify your steps.\nProblem 5. (15: 10,5 points)\n(a) Compute ∫C z1/3 dz, where C the unit semicircle shown. Use the principal branch of\narg(z) to compute the cube root.\nIm z\nRe z\nC\n-1\n(b) Repeat using the branch with π ≤ arg(z) < 3π.\nProblem 6. (10 points)\nUse the fundamental theorem for complex line integrals to show that f(z) = 1/z cannot\npossibly have an antiderivative defined on C - {0}.\nProblem 7. (10 points)\nDoes Re (∫C f(z) dz) = ∫C Re(f(z)) dz? If so prove it, if not give a counterexample.\nProblem 8. (10 points)\nAre the following simply connected?\n(i) The punctured plane.\n(ii) The cut plane: C -{nonnegative real axis}.\n(iii) The part of the plane inside a circle.\n(iv) The part of the plane outside a circle.\n\nMIT OpenCourseWare\nhttps://ocw.mit.edu\n18.04 Complex Variables with Applications\nSpring 2018\nFor information about citing these materials or our Terms of Use, visit: https://ocw.mit.edu/terms."
