      "content": "18.04 Problem Set 6, Spring 2018\nCalendar\nMar. 19-23: Reading: Topic 7 notes (Taylor and Laurent series)\nApr. 2-6: Reading: Topic 8 (Residue theorem)\nComing next\nApr. 9-13: Applications of the residue theorem.\nProblem 1. (12 points)\nSay whether the following series converge or diverge.\ninf\nn\ninf\ninf\nn\ninf\n(1 + 2i\n( 1 -i\nn!\n(a) ∑\n(b) ∑ in\n(c) ∑\n(d) ∑\n1 -i )\n1 + 2i )\n10n\nn=0\nn=0\nn=0\nn=0\nProblem 2. (8 points)\nFind the radius of convergence.\ninf z3n\n(a) f1(z) = ∑ 2n\n(b) f2(z) = 1 + 3(z -1) + 3(z -1)2 + (z -1)3\nn=0\nProblem 3. (8 points)\ninf\nSuppose the radius of convergence of ∑ anzn is R.\nFind the radius of convergence of\nn=0\neach of the following.\ninf\ninf\n(a) ∑ anz2n\n(b) ∑ n-nanzn\nn=0\nn=1\nProblem 4. (10 points)\n(a) Give a function f that is analytic in the punctured plane (C - {1}), has a simple zero\nat z = 0 and an essential singularity at z = 1.\n(b) Suppose f is analytic and has a zero of order m at z0. Show that g(z) = f′(z)/f(z)\nhas a simple pole at z0 with Res(g, z0) = m.\nProblem 5. (20 points)\n(a) What is the order of the pole of f1(z) =\nat z = 0.\n(2 cos(z) - 2 + z2)2\nHint: Work with 1/f1(z).\nz2 + 1\n(b) Find the residue of f2(z) =\nat z = 0.\n2z cos(z)\nez\n(c) Let f3(z) =\nFind all the isolated singularities and compute the residue at\nz(z + 1)3 .\neach one.\n(d) Find the residue at infinity of f4(z) = 1 - z .\n\n18.04 Problem Set 6, Spring 2018\ncos(z)\n(e) Let f5(z) =\n∫0\nzf(w) dw\n, where f(z) is analytic and f(0) = 1. Find the residue at\nz = 0.\nProblem 6. (10 points)\nWrite the principal part of each function at the isolated singularity. Compute the corre\nsponding residue.\n(a) f1(z) = z3e1/z\n1 - cosh(z)\n(b) f2(z) =\nz3\nProblem 7. (8 points)\n(a) Let f(z) = (1+z)a, computed using the principal branch of log. Give the Taylor series\naround 0.\n(b) Does the principal branch of √z have a Laurent expansion in the domain 0 < |z|?\nProblem 8. (15 points)\nUsing variations of the geometric series find the following series expansions of\nf(z) = 4 - z2\nabout z0 = 1.\n(a) The Taylor series. What is the radius of convergence?\n(b) The Laurent series on 1 < |z -1| < R1. What is R1?\n(c) The Laurent series for |z -1| > 3.\nProblem 9. (15 points)\neiz\n(a) Use the residue theorem to compute ∫\nz2(z - 2)(z + 5i) dz.\n|z|=3\n(b) Evaluate ∫\ne1/z sin(1/z) dz.\n|z|=1\n(c) Explain why Cauchy's integral formula can be viewed as a special case of the residue\ntheorem.\nProblem 10. (15 points)\ninf\nIn this problem we will compute ∑ n\n2 using the residue theorem. The techniques learned\nhere are general. In particular, the\n-inf\nuse of cot(πz) is fairly common.\nLet φ(z) = π cot(πz) = π cos(πz)\n(a)\nsin(πz) . At all the singular points give the order of the pole\nand the residue.\n(b) Take the contour CN which is the square with vertices at ±(N + 1/2) ± i(N + 1/2).\nUse the Cauchy residue theorem to write an expression for\nπ cot(πz)\n∫\ndz.\nz2\nCN\n\n18.04 Problem Set 6, Spring 2018\nYou'll need to do some work to compute the residue at z = 0.\n(c) We'll tell you that | cot(πz)| < 2 along the contour CN . Use this to show that\nπ cot(πz)\nlim ∫\ndz = 0.\nN→inf\nz2\nCN\ninf 1\n(d) Use parts (b) and (c) to compute ∑ n2 .\nn=1\nProblems below here are not assigned. Do them just for fun.\nProblem Fun 1. (No points)\ninf zn\ninf zn\ninf\nBy considering the 3 series\n∑\n∑\n∑ zn,\nshow that a power series may\nn2 ,\nn ,\nn=1\nn=1\nn=1\nconverge on all, some or no points on the boundary of its disk of convergence.\nProblem Fun 2. (No points)\nSuppose that there exists a function f(z) which is analytic at z = 0 and which satisfies the\ndifferential equation\n(1 + z)f′(z) = 2f(z), with f(0) = 1.\n(a) Solve this equation to get a closed-form expression for f(z).\n(b) Find the formula for the power series coefficients of f(z) directly from the differential\nequation.\n(c) Check your answer to part(b) against the Taylor series obtained by expanding out the\nclosed-form expression for the solution found in part (a).\nProblem Fun 3. (No points) Show that | cot(πz)| < 2 along the contour in problem 10.\nHint, show that along the vertical sides | cot(πz)| < 1, while along the horizontal sides\n| cot(πz)| < 2.\ninf\nProblem Fun 4. (No points) Suppose the radius of convergence of ∑ anzn is R. Show\nn=0\ninf\nthat the radius of convergence of ∑ n2anzn is also R.\nn=0\n\nMIT OpenCourseWare\nhttps://ocw.mit.edu\n18.04 Complex Variables with Applications\nSpring 2018\nFor information about citing these materials or our Terms of Use, visit: https://ocw.mit.edu/terms."
