      "content": "18.04 Problem Set 7, Spring 2018\nCalendar\nApr. 9-13: Topic 9 notes (definite integrals)\nComing next\nApr. 18-20: Conformal mapping\nProblem 1. (21 points)\n2π\n8 dθ\n(a) Compute ∫\n5 + 2 cos(θ).\n2π\ndθ\n(b) Compute ∫\n(3 + 2 cos(θ))2 .\n2π\nsin2(θ)\n2π\n(c) Compute ∫\na+ b cos(θ) dθ, a > |b| > 0.\n(Answer: b2 (a -\n√\na2 - b2).)\nProblem 2. (21 points)\ninf\ndx\n(a) Compute ∫\nx2 + 2x+ 2. (Answer: π).\n-inf\nx2\n(b) Compute ∫\ninf\n(Answer: π/3.)\n(x2 + 1)(x2 + 4) dx.\n-inf\ninf\n2π\n√\n(c) Show ∫\nx3 + 1 dx =\nby integrating around the boundary of the circular sector\nshown and letting R →inf. The vertex angle of the sector is 2π/3.\nRe(z)\nIm(z)\nR\nCircular sector with vertex angle 2π/3.\nProblem 3. (14 points)\ninf cos(2x)\n(a) Compute ∫\nx2 + 1 dx.\n-inf\ninf cos(2x)\n(b) Compute ∫\n(x2 + 1)2 dx. (Answer: 3π/(2e2).)\n-inf\nPrincipal value.\nRecall if f(x) is continuous on the real axis except at, say, two points x1 < x2 then the\n\n18.04 Problem Set 7, Spring 2018\nprincipal value of the integral along the entire x-axis is defined by\ninf\nx1-r1\nx2-r2\nR\np.v. ∫\n= lim [∫\nf(x) dx+ ∫\nf(x) dx+ ∫\nf(x) dx.]\n-inf\n-R\nx1+r1\nx2+r2\nHere the limit is taken as R →inf, r1 →0, r2 →0. The extension to more points of\ndiscontinuity should be clear.\nProblem 4. (14 points)\ninf e3ix\n(a) Compute p.v. ∫\nx - 2i dx.\n-inf\ninf cos(x)\nif Im(w) > 0\n(b) Derive the formula p.v. ∫\n-πie-iw\nx - w dx = {πieiw\nif Im(w) < 0.\n-inf\nProblem 5. (14 points)\ninf\neix\n(a) Derive the formula p.v. ∫\n(x - 1)(x - 2) dx = πi(e2i - ei).\n-inf\nsin2(x)\n(b) Derive the formula ∫\ninf\ndx = π/2.\nx2\n1 - cos(2x)\n2 Re(1 - e2ix).\nHint: sin2(x) =\n=\nProblem 6. (7 points)\ninf\n√x\nCompute ∫\nx2 + 1 dx. (Answer: π/\n√\n2.)\nProblem 7. (15 points)\nLet f(x) = {1 for -1 < x < 1\n0 elsewhere.\n\nf(x)e-iωx dx.\n(a) (5) Solution: Compute the Fourier transform f(ω) = ∫\ninf\n-inf\n(b) (10) Show that the formula for the Fourier inverse gives f(x). That is, show\ninf\nf(ω)eiωx dω.\nf(x) = 1\n\n2π ∫\n-inf\nHint: this will require an indented contour around 0.\nProblems below here are not assigned. Do them just for fun.\nProblem Fun.1. (No points)\n(a) Let f(x) = e-x2 . Let ω > 0 and I = ∫\ninf\nf(x)ei2ωx dx. Use the rectangle with\n\n18.04 Problem Set 7, Spring 2018\ninf\nvertices at 0, R, R + iω and iω and the known integral ∫ e-x2 dx = √π/2 to show that\nI = e-ω2√π/2+iB. Here B is the imaginary part and we are not concerned with its value.\n\n(b) Now use part (a) and symmetry to show that the Fourier transform f(ω) = ∫\ninf\nf(x)e-iωx dx =\n-inf\n√πe-ω2/4.\nProblem Fun.2. (No points)\n2π\n2π ⋅ (2n)!\nCompute ∫\n(cos θ)2n dθ. For n = 1, 2, .... (Answer: 22n(n!)2 .)\nProblem Fun.3. (No points)\ninf\nx2\nCompute p.v. ∫\n(x2 + 1)2 dx.\n-inf\ninf\nx2\nIs this the same as the integral ∫\n(x2 + 1)2 dx without the principal value?\n-inf\n\nMIT OpenCourseWare\nhttps://ocw.mit.edu\n18.04 Complex Variables with Applications\nSpring 2018\nFor information about citing these materials or our Terms of Use, visit: https://ocw.mit.edu/terms."
