      "content": "18.04 Problem Set 8, Spring 2018\nCalendar\nApr. 23-28: Reading: Topic 10 (Conformal maps)\nComing next\nMay 1-5: Applications\nProblem 1. (15 points)\nLet z = x+ iy. Describe the image of each of the following regions under the mapping\nw = ez.\n(a) The strip 0 < y < π.\n(b) The slanted strip between the lines y = x and y = x+ 2π.\n(c) The half-strip x > 0, 0 < y < π.\n(d) The rectangle 1 < x < 2, 0 < y < π.\n(e) The right half-plane x > 0.\nProblem 2. (18 points)\n(a) Find a fractional linear transformation that maps the right half-plane to the unit disk\nsuch that the origin is mapped to -1.\n(b)\nA fixed point z of a transformation T is one where T(z) = z. Let T be a fractional\nlinear transformation. Assume T is not the identity map. Show T has a most two fixed\npoints.\n(c) Let S be a circle and z1 a point not on the circle. Show that there is exactly one point\nz2 such that z1 and z2 are symmetric with respect to S.\n(Hint: start by proving this for S a line.)\nProblem 3. (20 points)\nSuppose you want to find a function u harmonic on the right half-plane that takes the values\nu(0, y) = y/(1 + y2) on the imaginary axis. The first obvious guess is u(z) = Im(z/(1 - z2).\nBut this fails because z/(1-z2) has a singularity at z = 1. Find a valid u using the following\nsteps.\nSo, forget about this guess and go back to only knowing that u is harmonic and u(0, y) =\ny/(1 + y2).\n(a) Show that rotation by α is a fractional linear transformation which corresponds to the\nmatrix (eiα/2\ne-iα/2).\n(This is not hard, it's just here in case you need it in part (b).)\n(b) Find a fractional linear transformation that maps the right half-plane to the unit disk,\nso that u is transformed to a function φ with φ(eiθ) = sin(θ)/2.\n\n18.04 Problem Set 8, Spring 2018\nHint: make sure 1 is mapped to 0. If your transformation still doesn't transform u to the\ncorrect φ try composing with a rotation.\n(c) Show that φ(w) = 2\n1 Im(w).\n(d) Use the fractional linear transform to take φ back to u on the right half-plane.\nProblem 4. (12 points)\n(a) Show that the mapping w = z + 1/z maps the circle |z| = a (a = 1) to the ellipse\nu2\nv2\n(a + 1/a)\n2 +\n(a - 1/a)\n2 = 1.\n(b) Where does it map the circle |z| = 1?\n(This problem will be helful when we look at Joukowsky transformations.)\nProblem 5. (24 points)\n(a) Find a harmonic function u on the upper half-plane that has the following boundary\nvalues.\n⎧1\nfor x < -1\n{\nu(x, 0) =\nfor -1 < x < 1\n⎨\n{\n⎩1\nfor 1 < x\n(b) Find a harmonic function, u(x, y), on the unit disk that boundary values indicated in\nthe figure.\nRe(z)\nIm(z)\neiπ/4\ne-iπ/4\nu = 0\nu = 1\n⎧1\nfor -π < θ < π/4\n{\nThat is, u(eiθ) =\nfor -π/4 < θ < π/4\n⎨\n{\n⎩1\nfor π/4 < θ < π\n(c) Find a harmonic function, u(x, y), on the infinite wedge with angle π/4 shown. Such\nthat u has the boundary values indicated in the figure.\n\n18.04 Problem Set 8, Spring 2018\nRe(z)\nIm(z)\neiπ/4\nu = 0\nu = 0\nu = 1\nu = 1\n\nMIT OpenCourseWare\nhttps://ocw.mit.edu\n18.04 Complex Variables with Applications\nSpring 2018\nFor information about citing these materials or our Terms of Use, visit: https://ocw.mit.edu/terms."
