      "source_url": "https://ocw.mit.edu/courses/18-04-complex-variables-with-applications-spring-2018/mit18_04_s18_pset01_sol.pdf",
      "content": "18.04 Problem Set 1, Spring 2018 Solutions\nProblem 1. (30: 10,5,10,5 points)\n(a) Let z1 = 1 + i, z2 = 1 + 3i. Compute z1z2, z1/z2, z1\nz2 (use the principal branch of log).\n(Give z1z2 and z1/z2 in standard rectangular form and z1\nz2 in polar form.)\nz1\n1 + i 1 -3i\n4 -2i\n2 - i\nSolution: z1 = 1+i, z2 = 1+3i: z1z2 = -2 + 4i ,\n=\n⋅\n=\n.\nz2\n1 + 3i 1 -3i =\ny\nz1 = 1 + i\n|z1| =\n√\n2, Arg(z1) = π/4 (principal branch).\nSo log(z1) = log(\n√\n2) + i π = 2 log(2) + iπ\n4 (principal branch).\nx\nThus,\nz1\nz2 = ez2 log(z1) = e(1+3i)(log(2)/2+iπ/4) = elog(2)/2-3π/4ei(3 log(2)/2+π/4) (not pretty!)\n(b) Compute all the values of ii. Say which one comes from the principal branch of log.\n(Give all your answers in standard form.)\nIs it surprising that ii is real?\nSolution: |i| = 1 and Arg(i) = π/2, so log(i) = π\n2 i + 2nπi, where n is any integer. Thus\nii = ei log(i) = e-π/2-2nπ\nOn the principal branch ii = e-π/2. I'm surprised that it's real!\n(c) Let z = 1 + i\n√\n3.\n(i) Compute z8. (Give your answer in standard form.)\n(ii) Find all the 4th roots of z.\nSolution: (i) z = 1 +\n√\n3 i = 2eiπ/3, so\nz8 = 256ei8π/3 = 256ei2π/3 = 128(-1 +\n√\n3 i)\n(ii) z1/4 = (2eiπ/3+2nπi)1/4 = 21/4eiπ/12, 21/4ei7π/12, 21/4ei13π/12, 21/4ei19π/12\nSince π/12 = 15∘ this doesn't have a pretty standard form, so we'll leave them as is. We\ncan always get numerical approximations if needed.\n(d) Copy the following figure and add all the 5th roots of z to it. (The figure indicates that\n|z| = 2.5. The circle on the outside is a handy protractor marked off in 10∘ increments.)\n\n18.04 Problem Set 1, Spring 2018 Solutions\nRe\nIm\n2.5\nz\n-2\n-2\n-1\n-1\nSolution: We have arg(z) = 70∘ = 7π/18, so z = 2.5ei7π/18. The roots are shown in orange.\nThe root in the first quadrant closest to the x-axis has argument arg(z)/5 = 7π/90 = 14∘.\nThe others are spaced at intervals of 2π/5 (72∘) around the circle of radius |z|1/5 = (2.5)1/5.\nRe\nIm\n2.5\nz\n-2\n-2\n-1\n-1\nradius 2.51/5\nProblem 2. (15: 5,5,5 points)\n= ez\n(a) Show ez\n.\nSolution: Let z = x+ iy, then ez = exeiy = ex cos(y) + iex sin(y). So,\n(ez) = ex cos(y) - iex sin(y) = exe-iy = ex-iy = ez\n(b) Show that if |z| = 1 then z-1 = z.\nSolution: We'll give two ways to say this:\nz\nz\nz\nMethod 1:\n=\n=\n= 1 = z.\nz\nz ⋅ z\n|z|2\nMethod 2: z = eiθ, so by part (a) z = e-iθ = z-1.\n\n18.04 Problem Set 1, Spring 2018 Solutions\n(c) Let x+iy = a + ib. Show that a2 + b2 = 1.\nx-iy\nHint: This takes one line if you look at it right. Think polar form.\nx+ iy\nreiθ\ne2iθ\nSolution: If x+ iy = reiθ, then x-iy = re-iθ. So, ∣\n∣= ∣\n∣= |\n| = 1.\nQED\nx-iy\nre-iθ\nProblem 3. (15: 5,10 points)\n(a) Sketch the curve z = et(1+i), where -inf < t < inf.\nSolution: et(1+i) = eteit. So as t grow the magnitude grows exponentially and the argument\nincreases. This gives a spiral!\nRe(z)\nIm(z)\nNote, this is not to scale. The exponential et grows too quickly, so we drew e0.2t instead.\nQualitatively this is a good representation of the curve.\n(b) Consider the mapping z → w = z2. Draw the image in the w-plane of the triangular\nregion in the z-plane with vertices 0, 1 and i.\nSolution: The figure shows the image.\nIn brief we have: z = 1 ↦ w = 1, z = (1 + i)/2 ↦ w = i/2, z = i↦w = -1.\nThe sides of the triangle map as follows:\nthe line segment [0, 1] ↦ the line segment [0, 1]\nthe line segment [0, i] ↦ the line segment [0, -1]\nthe line segment [1, i] ↦ the parabola shown in the figure (proved below).\nRe(z)\nIm(z)\n(1 + i)/2\ni\nRe(w)\nIm(w)\n-1\n0.5i\nz 7→w = z2\nIt takes a small amount of algebra to find the equation for the image of the segment\nfrom 1 to i. We parametrize the segment as z = (1 -t) + ti with 0 ≤t ≤ 1. Then\nw= z2 = (1 -2t) + 2t(1 -t)i. As a curve in the plane this is\nw = (u(t), v(t)), where u(t) = 1 - 2t and v(t) = 2t(1 - t).\nA little more algebra shows that t = (1 -u)/2 and therefore v = -u2 + 1/2. This is the\n\n18.04 Problem Set 1, Spring 2018 Solutions\nformula for the parabola shown.\nProblem 4. (10 points)\nLet zk = e2πi/n. Show\n1 + zk + zk\n2 + zk\n3 + ... + zk\nn-1 = 0\nHint: The polynomial zn -1 has one easy root. Use that to factor it into a linear term and\na degree n - 1 term.\nSolution: The nth roots of 1 are all the roots of the equation zn-1 = 0. Since we know\nthat z = 1 is a root we can factor the equation as\n(z -1)(zn-1 + zn-2 + ... + z + 1) = 0\nSince zk is also a root of zn -1 and zk =1, we must have zk is a root of the second factor.\nThis is what we were asked to show!\nProblem 5. (20: 10,10 points) (Orthogonal lines stay orthogonal!)\n(a) Consider the mapping w = ez.\n(i) Sketch in the w-plane the image under this mapping of vertical lines in the z-plane.\n(ii) On the same graph sketch the image of horizontal lines.\nShow enough lines to give a good idea of what's happening.\n(iii) Show (argue either geometrically or analytically) that the images of a vertical and a\nhorizontal lines meet at right angles.\nSolution: (i) As usual, let z = x+ iy. Vertical line have the equation x = a for some\nconstant a. We can parametrize this line by z = a+ iy, with -inf< y < inf. The image of\nthe line under the mapping is\nw = ea+iy = eaeiy.\nThus |w| = ea is constant, so the image is a circle of radius ea centered on 0.\n(ii) Likewise, horizontal lines have the equation y = b for some constant b. We parametrize\nthis by z = x+ ib, with -inf < x < inf. The image of the line under this mapping is\nw = ex+ib = exeib.\nThus arg(w) = b is constant, so the image is a ray from the origin at angle b.\nIn the figure below we label the corresponding curves with the same label. So, for example,\nthe image of the vertical line lv4 is the circle in the w-plane labeled lv4\n\n18.04 Problem Set 1, Spring 2018 Solutions\nRe(z)\nIm(z)\nlv1\nlv2\nlv3\nlv4\nlh1\nlh2\nlh3\nlh4\nlh5\nlh6\nlh7\nlh8\n-1\n1/2\nπ/4 i\nπ/2 i\n3π/4 i\nπ i\n-3π/4 i\n-π/2 i\n-π/4 i\nRe(w)\nIm(w)\nlv1\nlv2\nlv3\nlv4\nlh1\nlh2\nlh3\nlh4\nlh5\nlh6\nlh7\nlh8\nz 7→w = ez\n(iii) The images found in parts (i) and (ii) are circles and rays. Geometrically we know\nthat radii are perpendicular to circles, so rays from the origin are perpendicular to circles\ncentered on the origin.\n(b) Repeat part (a) for the mapping w = z2.\nSolution: This part is similar to part (a), though we will need a little more algebraic\nmanipulation to identify the image curves.\n(i) The vertical line x = a is parametrized by z = a+ iy, with -inf < y < inf. So the image\nis w = a2 -y2 + i2ay. Let's write this as w = u+ iv. It is easy to see that with u = a2 -y2\nand v = 2ay we have\nu = a2 - (v/2a)2.\nThis is a parabola in the uv-plane which opens to the left and has vertex at (a2, 0).\n(ii) Horizontal lines y = b are similar:\nParametrization: z = x+ ib, with -inf < x < inf.\nImage: w = x2 - b2 + i2bx.\nIf w = u+ iv then u = (v/2b)2 - b2. This is a parabola opening to the right with vertex at\n(-b2, 0).\nThe figure below is labeled in the same way as the figure in part (a). Notice the vertical\nlines x = a and x = -a map to the same parabola as befits the 2-to-1 mapping w = z2.\nThe real z-axis (x = 0) maps to the positive real w-axis (u > 0). We can view this as a\ndegenerate parabola. Likewise for the imaginary z-axis.\nRe(z)\nIm(z)\nlv1\nlv2\nlv3\nlv4\nlv5\nlh1\nlh2\nlh3\nlh4\nlh5\n-1\n-1\nRe(w)\nIm(w)\nlv2, lv4\nlv1, lv5\nlh2, lh4\nlh1, lh5\nlh3\nlv3\nz 7→w = z2\n(iii) To show the image curves are orthogonal (meet at right angles) we need to show that\ntheir tangent vectors are orthogonal. Happily, we've parametrized the image curves in parts\n(i) and (ii), so computing tangent vectors is easy. In keeping with the course we will write\nvectors as x + iy rather than in 18.02 notation as ⟨x, y⟩\n\n18.04 Problem Set 1, Spring 2018 Solutions\nHorizontal line: z = a+iy; image w = a2-y2+i2ay; image tangent vector: dw = -2y+i2a.\nVertical line: z = x+ ib; image w = x2 - b2 + i2xb; image tangent vector:\ndy\ndw = 2x + i2b.\ndx\nThe lines meet at the point a + ib, so we need to check the tangents at that point.\nHorizontal line image: dw = -2b + i2a\nVertical line image: dw\ndy\n= 2a + i2b\ndx\nIt is easy to see that these are orthogonal. For 18.04 the nicest way to say this is to note\nthat -2b + i2a = i(2a + i2b). Since multiplication by i is rotation by 90∘ the vectors are at\nright angles.\nExtra problems not for points\nProblem 6. (0 points) Find all points where\nArg (z -1\nz + 2) = ±π\nHint: let w = (z-1)/z+ 2). What does the condition say about the relation between w and\nw? Be careful to note points where Arg(w) is not defined.\nSolution: Answer: the set of points is the circle |z + 1/2| = 3/2, excluding the points z = 1\nand z = -2 where arg(w) is not defined.\nJustification. Arg(w) = ±π/2 means that w is on the imaginary axis (and w = 0). Thus\nwe must have\nz -1\nw= z+ 2 = ib, where b = 0 is real.\n2ib + 1\nSolving for z we get z = -ib + 1.\nWe can view this as a mapping b ↦ z from the real b-line to the complex z-plane. A tiny\namount of algebra gives\n2ib+ 1\nz = -ib+ 1 = -ib+ 1 -2.\nIgnoring the scale by 3 and the shift by -2 for the moment we have:\nClaim. The image of w = -ib+1 where b is real is the circle |w - 1/2| = 1/2, i.e. the circle\nwith radius 1/2 and center 1/2.\nProof.\n1 + bi\n|w-1/2| = ∣\n∣\n∣= 2.\n-ib + 1 - 1/2∣ = 2(1 - bi)\n(The last equality follow from problem 2c.)\nSince z = 3w-2 we have the z-image is the circle of radius 3/2 with center 3/2-2 = -1/2.\nz -1\nAlternative solution. w = (z-1)/(z+ 2) is pure imaginary, so w = -w, i.e.\n=\nz + 2\n-z -1\nz + 2. A little algebra gives 2|z|2 + z + z = 4.\nLet z = x+ iy. The above becomes 2(x2 + y2) + 2x = 4 or x2 + y2 + x = 4. Completing the\nsquare gives (x + 1/2)2 + y2 = 9/4. That is |z + 1/2|2 = 9/4.\n\n18.04 Problem Set 1, Spring 2018 Solutions\n\nMIT OpenCourseWare\nhttps://ocw.mit.edu\n18.04 Complex Variables with Applications\nSpring 2018\nFor information about citing these materials or our Terms of Use, visit: https://ocw.mit.edu/terms."
