      "content": "18.04 Problem Set 8, Spring 2018 Solutions\nProblem 1. (15 points)\nLet z = x+ iy. Describe the image of each of the following regions under the mapping\nw = ez.\n(a) The strip 0 < y < π.\n= reiθ\n= exeiy\nSolution: For this entire problem let's write ez\n. Since ez\n, we have\nr = ex,\nθ= y\nIn the strip, ex takes all values > 0. So, the image is every point with 0 < θ < π, i.e.\nthe upper half-plane.\n(b) The slanted strip between the lines y = x and y = x+ 2π.\nSolution: Both the boundary lines y = x and y = x+ 2π map to the exponential spiral\nshown. Each of the two vertical segments on the left are of length 2π. So ez maps this\nsegment to a full circle minus the point ex+ix = ex+i(x+2π). In this way, the slanted strip is\nmapped to the entire plane minus the spiral and minus the origin.\nx\ny\ny = x\ny = x + 2π\nRe(w)\nIm(w)\nw = ez\n(c) The half-strip x > 0, 0 < y < π.\nSince r = ex > 1, the image is outside the unit circle. Since 0 < θ = y < π, the image is in\nthe upper half plane.\nAnswer: The part of the upper half-plane outside the unit circle.\nx\ny\nπ\nRe(w)\nIm(w)\n-1\nw = ez\n(d) The rectangle 1 < x < 2, 0 < y < π.\nSolution: As before, since 0 < θ = y < π, the image is in the upper half-plane. The left and\nright edges of the rectangle map to the semicircles of radius e1 and e2 respectively. The top\nand bottom edges map to segments along the real axis\n\n18.04 Problem Set 8, Spring 2018 Solutions\nAnswer: The image is the half annulus shown.\nx\ny\nπ\nRe(w)\nIm(w)\ne1\ne2\n-e1\n-e2\nw = ez\n(e) The right half-plane x > 0.\nSolution: Since r = ex > 0 this maps to the exterior of the unit circle.\nx\ny\nπ\nRe(w)\nIm(w)\nw = ez\nProblem 2. (18 points)\n(a) Find a fractional linear transformation that maps the right half-plane to the unit disk\nsuch that the origin is mapped to -1.\nz -1\nSolution: T(z) = z+ 1 . To verify this works we need to check three things.\n1. T(0) = -1. This is obvious.\n2. T maps the boundary of the right half-plane (y-axis) to the boundary of the unit disk\n(unit circle).\n3. T maps the right half-plane to the inside of the disk.\n|iy - 1|\nTo see (2): Take iy on the boundary of the half-plane. Then, |T (iy)| =\n=\n|iy + 1|\n√1 + y2\n= 1. This shows T (iy) is on the unit circle. Since we know fractional linear\n√1 + y2\ntransformations map lines to lines or circles this shows the image of the y-axis must be the\nentire unit circle.\nTo see (3): (1) shows that one point in the right half-plane maps to the inside of the disk.\nThis implies the entire half-plane must do so also.\n(b) A fixed point z of a transformation T is one where T(z) = z. Let T be a fractional\nlinear transformation. Assume T is not the identity map. Show T has a most two fixed\n\n18.04 Problem Set 8, Spring 2018 Solutions\npoints.\naz + b\nLet T (z) =\nTo find fixed points we solve the equation T(z) = z. A little algebra\ncz + d .\nputs the equation in the form\naz + b = z ⇔ cz2 + (d-a)z-b = 0.\ncz + d\nThere are a number of cases to consider. In all of them the number of fixed points is at\nmost two.\nIf c =0 then the quadratic equation has at most two solutions. (It might have only one if\nit has a repeated root.)\nIf c = 0 then the equation is linear and there is at most one solution. (There may be none.)\n(c) Let S be a circle and z1 a point not on the circle. Show that there is exactly one point\nz2 such that z1 and z2 are symmetric with respect to S.\n(Hint: start by proving this for S a line.)\nThis is in the topic 10 notes in section 10.3.2:\nLet T be a fractional linear transformation that maps S to a line. We know that w1 = T (z1)\nhas a unique reflection w2 in this line. Since T -1 preserves symmetry, z1 and z2 = T -1(w2)\nare symmetric in S. Since w2 is the unique point symmetric to w1 the same is true for z2\nvis-a-vis z1.\nx\ny\nz1\nz2 = T -1(w2)\nS\nx\ny\nw1 = T(z1)\nw2\nT(S)\nw = T(z)\nProblem 3. (20 points)\nSuppose you want to find a function u harmonic on the right half-plane that takes the values\nu(0, y) = y/(1 + y2) on the imaginary axis. The first obvious guess is u(z) = Im(z/(1 - z2).\nBut this fails because z/(1-z2) has a singularity at z = 1. Find a valid u using the following\nsteps.\nSo, forget about this guess and go back to only knowing that u is harmonic and u(0, y) =\ny/(1 + y2).\n(a) Show that rotation by α is a fractional linear transformation which corresponds to the\nmatrix (eiα/2\ne-iα/2).\n(This is not hard, it's just here in case you need it in part (b).)\neiα/2z\nSolution: T(z) =\n= eiαz. This is indeed rotation by α.\ne-iα/2\n\n18.04 Problem Set 8, Spring 2018 Solutions\n(b) Find a fractional linear transformation that maps the right half-plane to the unit disk,\nso that u is transformed to a function φ with φ(eiθ) = sin(θ)/2.\nHint: make sure 1 is mapped to 0. If your transformation still doesn't transform u to the\ncorrect φ try composing with a rotation.\nSolution: Conveniently, the map found in problem 2a will work. Write w = T(z), so z is\nthe variable on the half-plane and w is the variable on the disk. We have the following ways\nof describing the φ.\nu(z) = φ ∘ T (z)\nor\nφ(w) = u ∘ T -1(w).\nw + 1\nWe have T -1(w) =\nWe know that T -1 maps unit circle eiθ to the imaginary axis\n-w + 1.\niy. (Don't lose track of i multiplying the y!) so we have\neiθ+ 1\n1 + eiθ\niy = T -1(eiθ) =\nequivalently\ny=\n⋅\n-eiθ+ 1\ni 1 - eiθ\nNow we can compute\ni ( 1+eiθ\ny\n1-eiθ)\n(1 + eiθ)(1 - eiθ)\nφ(eiθ) = u(0, y) =\n=\n=\n⋅\n1 + y2\ni (1 - eiθ)2 - (1 + eiθ)2\n1 - ( 1+eiθ\n1-eiθ )\ni (1 - ei2θ\neiθ - e-iθ\n-4eiθ ) = e-iθ - eiθ\n=\n=\n⋅\n= 2 sin(θ).\n-4i\n2i\nThis is exactly what was asserted in the problem.\n(c) Show that φ(w) = 2\n1 Im(w).\nSolution: The point is that we are looking for a function φ(w) which is\n1. a harmonic function on the disk\n2. has boundary value φ(eiθ) = sin(θ)/2. That is, if w = eiθ then we need to have\nφ(w) = sin(θ)/2.\nThe function Φ(w) = w is analytic, so φ(w) = 2\n1 Im(w) is harmonic. On the boundary of\nthe disk we have\nφ(eiθ) = 2 Im(eiθ) = 2 sin(θ).\nThis is exactly what is required by requirement (2) above.\n(d) Use the fractional linear transform to take φ back to u on the right half-plane.\nSolution: The relationship u(z) = φ(T (z)) gives\nu(z) = φ(z-1\n2 Im (z -1\nz+ 1) =\nz+ 1) .\nSo, using z = x+ iy\n2 Im ((x - 1) + iy\ny\nu(x, y) = 1\n(x+ 1) + iy ) = (x+ 1)2 + y2 .\n\n18.04 Problem Set 8, Spring 2018 Solutions\nProblem 4. (12 points)\n(a) Show that the mapping w = z + 1/z maps the circle |z| = a (a = 1) to the ellipse\nu2\nv2\n(a + 1/a)\n2 +\n(a - 1/a)\n2 = 1.\nSolution: We'll use the notation w = u+ iv. We'll write points on the circle |z| = a as aeiθ.\nSo,\naeiθ +\nw= z+ 1 =\nz\naeiθ\n= (a cos(θ) + ia sin(θ)) + cos(θ) - i sin(θ)\na\n= (a + a\n1) cos(θ) + i(a- a\n1) sin(θ).\nThis shows u= (a+ a\n1) cos(θ) and (a- a\n1) sin(θ). Now it is clear that\nu2\nv2\n= cos2(θ) + sin2(θ) = 1.\nQED\n(a + 1/a)\n2 +\n(a - 1/a)\n(b) Where does it map the circle |z| = 1?\n(This problem will be helful when we look at Joukowsky transformations.)\nSolution: If z = eiθ then the computation above shows that\nw = z + 1/z = 2 cos(θ).\nThat is, w is real. So the unit circle is mapped to the line segment -2 ≤ x ≤ 2. (As z goes\nonce around the circle, w covers the segment twice.)\nv\nu\n-2\na = 1.5\na = 2\na = 1\nProblem 5. (24 points)\n(a) Find a harmonic function u on the upper half-plane that has the following boundary\nvalues.\n⎧1\nfor x < -1\n{\nu(x, 0) =\nfor -1 < x < 1\n⎨\n{\n⎩1\nfor 1 < x\n\n18.04 Problem Set 8, Spring 2018 Solutions\nSolution: u(z) = 1 - π\n1 θ2 + π\n1 θ1 = 1 - π\n1 arg(z-1) + π\n1 arg(z + 1).\nx\ny\nx1 = -1\nx2 = 1\nu = 1\nu = 0\nu = 1\nz = x + iy\nθ1\nθ2\nHere θ1 = arg(z+1), θ2 = arg(z-1), with θ1 and θ2 between -π/2 and 3π/2. (We can choose\nany convenient branch cut that makes the argument analytic in the upper half-plane.)\n(b) Find a harmonic function, u(x, y), on the unit disk that boundary values indicated in\nthe figure.\nRe(z)\nIm(z)\neiπ/4\ne-iπ/4\nu = 0\nu = 1\n⎧1\nfor -π < θ < π/4\n{\nThat is, u(eiθ) =\nfor -π/4 < θ < π/4\n⎨\n{1\nfor π/4 < θ < π\n⎩\nSolution: Our strategy is to map the disk the the upper half-plane, solve the problem there\nand then translate back to the disk.\nMethod 1. Given our solution in part (a) we can find a fractional linear transformation\nT from the half-plane to the disk with\nT(inf) = -1,\nT(-1) = e-iπ/4,\nT (1) = eiπ/4.\nWith this map, our solution in part (a) on the half-plane would exactly correspond to the\n-w + a\nsolution we seek. Finding such a T is straightforward. We start with T (w) =\n. This\nw + b\nis chosen so that T(inf) = -1. Plugging in w = ±1 we get the equations\n1 + a = e-iπ/4 =\nT(-1) =\n√1\n-i√1\n-1 + b\n-1 + a = eiπ/4\nT(1) =\n= √1\n+ i √1\n.\n1 + b\n\n18.04 Problem Set 8, Spring 2018 Solutions\nThese are easy to solve for\na = √1\n+ i (1 +√\n√\n2),\nand\nb = i(1 +\n√\n2).\nIn any case, we will just use them as a and b.\nLet's call our solution in part (a) uH(w). So\nuH(w) = 1 - π\n1 θ2 + π\n1 θ1 = Re (1 - πi\n1 log(w - 1) + πi\n1 log(w + 1)) .\nThe connection between uH and the u we seek is u(z) = uH ∘ T -1(z). It's easy to compute\nbz - a\nthat w = T -1(z) = -z + 1, so\nπi log ( bz - a\nπi log ( bz - a\nu(z) = Re (1 - 1\n-z+ 1 -1) + 1\n-z+ 1 + 1))\nMethod 2. Here we just use our standard transform from the upper half-plane to the disk:\nz -i\nT(w) =\n= T-1(e-iπ/4). Then we can transform the problem\nz + i . Let w1 = T-1(eiπ/4), w2\nto the half-plane with jumps in the boundary value at w1 and w2. Solve this in the same\nmanner as part (a) and transfer the solution back to the disk. We leave the calculations to\nyou!\n(c) Find a harmonic function, u(x, y), on the infinite wedge with angle π/4 shown. Such\nthat u has the boundary values indicated in the figure.\nRe(z)\nIm(z)\neiπ/4\nu = 0\nu = 0\nu = 1\nu = 1\nSolution: Call the wedge W and call the variable on the wedge w. The map z = f(w) = w4\nmaps W to the upper half-plane, with f(eiπ/4) = -1 and f(1) = 1.\nSo the boundary value problem in this part is transformed to exactly the problem in part\n(a). If we call the solution in part (a) uH(z), then the solution we seek is\nu(w) = uH ∘ f(w) = uH(w4) = 1 - π\n1 arg(w4 -1) + π\n1 arg(w4 + 1).\n\nMIT OpenCourseWare\nhttps://ocw.mit.edu\n18.04 Complex Variables with Applications\nSpring 2018\nFor information about citing these materials or our Terms of Use, visit: https://ocw.mit.edu/terms."
